15
00:01:01.900 --> 00:01:04.170
Would God that any in thisnoble presence

16
00:01:04.170 --> 00:01:07.400
were enough noble to beupright judge of nobleRichard,

17
00:01:07.400 --> 00:01:08.600
then true noblesse would

18
00:01:08.600 --> 00:01:12.730
learn him forbearance fromso foul a wrong.

19
00:01:12.730 --> 00:01:16.070
What subject can givesentence on his king?

20
00:01:16.070 --> 00:01:19.600
And who stands here thatis not Richard's subject?

21
00:01:19.600 --> 00:01:22.230
Thieves are not judged butthey are by to hear,

22
00:01:22.230 --> 00:01:24.970
although apparent guilt beseen in them.

23
00:01:24.970 --> 00:01:27.970
And shall the figure ofGod's majesty,

24
00:01:27.970 --> 00:01:30.700
his captain, steward,deputy elect,

25
00:01:30.700 --> 00:01:34.830
anointed, crowned, plantedmany years,

26
00:01:34.830 --> 00:01:38.100
be judged by subject andinferior breath,

27
00:01:38.100 --> 00:01:40.130
and he himself notpresent?

28
00:01:40.130 --> 00:01:42.370
Oh, forfend it, God,

29
00:01:42.370 --> 00:01:44.130
that in a Christianclimate

30
00:01:44.130 --> 00:01:50.100
souls refined should showso heinous, black, obscenea deed.

31
00:01:50.100 --> 00:01:51.100
Traitor!

32
00:01:51.100 --> 00:01:54.600
I speak to subjects, and asubject speaks,

33
00:01:54.600 --> 00:01:58.030
stirred up by God, thusboldly for his king.

34
00:01:58.030 --> 00:02:02.530
My lord of Hereford here,whom you call king,

35
00:02:02.530 --> 00:02:05.730
is a foul traitor to proudHereford's king.

36
00:02:05.730 --> 00:02:11.770
And if you crown him, letme prophesy.

37
00:02:11.770 --> 00:02:16.430
The blood of English shallmanure the ground

38
00:02:16.430 --> 00:02:20.730
and future ages groan forthis foul act.

39
00:02:20.730 --> 00:02:23.670
Peace shall go sleep withTurks and infidels.

40
00:02:23.670 --> 00:02:25.030
And in this seat of peace,

41
00:02:25.030 --> 00:02:29.230
tumultuous wars shall kinwith kin and kind withkind confound.

42
00:02:29.230 --> 00:02:32.700
Disorder, horror, fear, andmutiny shall here inhabit,

43
00:02:32.700 --> 00:02:34.100
and this land be called

44
00:02:34.100 --> 00:02:38.570
the field of Golgotha anddead men's skulls.

45
00:02:38.570 --> 00:02:42.430
Oh, if you raise thishouse against this house,

46
00:02:42.430 --> 00:02:44.430
it will the woefullestdivision prove

47
00:02:44.430 --> 00:02:47.800
that ever fell upon thiscursed earth.

48
00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:52.930
Prevent it, resist it, letit not be so,

49
00:02:52.930 --> 00:02:59.030
lest child, child's children,cry against you woe.

50
00:03:00.100 --> 00:03:02.070
Well have you argued, sir,

51
00:03:02.070 --> 00:03:07.430
and, for your pains, ofcapital treason we arrestyou here.

52
00:03:07.430 --> 00:03:08.700
My lord of Westminster,

53
00:03:08.700 --> 00:03:11.430
be it your charge to keep himsafely till his day of trial.

54
00:03:15.800 --> 00:03:19.170
May it please you, lords,to grant the commons' suit.

55
00:03:19.170 --> 00:03:20.370
Aye!

56
00:03:21.900 --> 00:03:26.570
Fetch hither Richard, thatin common view he maysurrender,

57
00:03:26.570 --> 00:03:28.930
so we shall proceedwithout suspicion.

58
00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:31.470
I will be his conduct.

59
00:03:57.970 --> 00:04:01.470
Alack, why am I sent forto a king

60
00:04:01.470 --> 00:04:04.070
before I have shook offthe regal thoughts

61
00:04:04.070 --> 00:04:05.830
wherewith I reigned?

62
00:04:07.130 --> 00:04:08.730
I hardly yet have learned

63
00:04:08.730 --> 00:04:13.200
to insinuate, flatter,bow, and bend my knee.

64
00:04:14.430 --> 00:04:18.100
Give sorrow leave awhileto tutor me to thissubmission.

65
00:04:21.070 --> 00:04:24.200
Yet I well remember thefavors of these men.

66
00:04:25.630 --> 00:04:27.800
Were they not mine?

67
00:04:27.800 --> 00:04:31.570
Did they not sometime cry,"all hail" to me?

68
00:04:35.200 --> 00:04:39.230
So Judas did to Christ.

69
00:04:39.230 --> 00:04:43.600
But he, in 12, found truthin all but 1.

70
00:04:43.600 --> 00:04:47.370
I, in 12,000, none.

71
00:04:49.300 --> 00:04:51.330
God save the king!

72
00:04:55.030 --> 00:04:58.670
Will no man say amen?

73
00:04:58.670 --> 00:05:00.770
Am I both priest andclerk?

74
00:05:00.770 --> 00:05:02.500
Well, then, amen.

75
00:05:02.500 --> 00:05:05.500
God save the king.

76
00:05:05.500 --> 00:05:07.230
Although I be not he,

77
00:05:08.430 --> 00:05:13.570
and yet, amen, if heavendo think him me.

78
00:05:15.670 --> 00:05:17.870
To do what service am Isent for hither?

79
00:05:20.800 --> 00:05:23.270
To do that office of thineown goodwill

80
00:05:23.270 --> 00:05:25.800
which tired majesty didmake thee offer:

81
00:05:25.800 --> 00:05:30.270
the resignation of thystate and crown to HenryBolingbroke.

82
00:05:30.270 --> 00:05:31.730
Give me the crown.

83
00:05:45.200 --> 00:05:49.970
Here, cousin, seize thecrown.

84
00:05:51.370 --> 00:05:52.770
Here, cousin.

85
00:05:54.970 --> 00:05:58.330
On this side my hand, andon that side yours.

86
00:05:58.330 --> 00:06:00.900
Now is this golden crownlike a deep well

87
00:06:00.900 --> 00:06:03.570
that owes two buckets,filling one another,

88
00:06:03.570 --> 00:06:06.630
the emptier ever dancingin the air,

89
00:06:06.630 --> 00:06:09.870
the other down, unseen,and full of water.

90
00:06:09.870 --> 00:06:14.470
That bucket down and fullof tears am I,

91
00:06:14.470 --> 00:06:18.830
drinking my griefs whilstyou mount up on high.

92
00:06:18.830 --> 00:06:21.700
I thought you had beenwilling to resign.

93
00:06:21.700 --> 00:06:27.870
My crown I am, but stillmy griefs are mine.

94
00:06:27.870 --> 00:06:31.430
You may my glories and mystate depose,

95
00:06:31.430 --> 00:06:34.070
but not my griefs.

96
00:06:34.070 --> 00:06:36.600
Still am I king of those.

97
00:06:38.030 --> 00:06:41.100
Part of your cares yougive me with your crown.

98
00:06:41.100 --> 00:06:45.300
Your cares set up do notpluck my cares down.

99
00:06:45.300 --> 00:06:49.770
My care is loss of care,by old care done.

100
00:06:49.770 --> 00:06:54.600
Your care is gain of care,by new care won.

101
00:06:54.600 --> 00:07:00.300
The cares I give I have,though given away.

102
00:07:00.300 --> 00:07:05.770
They tend the crown, yetstill with me they stay.

103
00:07:07.670 --> 00:07:10.730
Are you contented toresign the crown?

104
00:07:14.700 --> 00:07:15.970
Aye.

105
00:07:20.770 --> 00:07:22.270
No!

106
00:07:26.630 --> 00:07:28.270
No.

107
00:07:30.570 --> 00:07:36.030
Aye, for I must nothingbe.

108
00:07:36.030 --> 00:07:42.400
Therefore no, no, for Iresign to thee.

109
00:07:44.270 --> 00:07:49.200
Now, mark me, how I willundo myself.

110
00:07:55.830 --> 00:07:59.530
I give this heavy weightfrom off my head

111
00:08:02.970 --> 00:08:07.400
and this unwieldy scepterfrom my hand,

112
00:08:09.270 --> 00:08:11.900
the pride of kingly swayfrom out my heart.

113
00:08:13.670 --> 00:08:17.300
With mine own tears I washaway my balm.

114
00:08:18.700 --> 00:08:24.570
With mine own hands I giveaway my crown.

115
00:08:24.570 --> 00:08:29.930
With mine own tongue denymy sacred state.

116
00:08:29.930 --> 00:08:35.270
With mine own breathrelease all duty's oaths.

117
00:08:35.270 --> 00:08:39.570
All pomp and majesty I doforswear.

118
00:08:39.570 --> 00:08:42.430
My manors, rents, revenuesI forego.

119
00:08:43.770 --> 00:08:47.400
My acts, decrees, andstatutes I deny.

120
00:08:49.100 --> 00:08:52.970
God pardon all oaths thatare broke to me.

121
00:08:54.430 --> 00:09:00.430
God keep all vows unbrokeare made to thee.

122
00:09:02.100 --> 00:09:08.230
Make me that nothing havewith nothing grieved,

123
00:09:08.230 --> 00:09:14.630
and thou with all pleasedthat hast all achieved.

124
00:09:14.630 --> 00:09:19.200
Long mayst thou live inRichard's seat to sit,

125
00:09:19.200 --> 00:09:23.000
and soon lie Richard in anearthly pit.

126
00:09:26.030 --> 00:09:34.930
God save King Henry,unkinged Richard says,

127
00:09:34.930 --> 00:09:40.070
and send him many years ofsunshine days.

128
00:09:44.500 --> 00:09:45.970
What more remains?

129
00:09:45.970 --> 00:09:47.330
No more, but that you read

130
00:09:47.330 --> 00:09:49.700
these accusations andthese grievous crimes

131
00:09:49.700 --> 00:09:51.400
committed by your personand your followers

132
00:09:51.400 --> 00:09:53.570
against the state andprofit of this land,

133
00:09:53.570 --> 00:09:55.500
that, by confessing them,

134
00:09:55.500 --> 00:09:58.170
the souls of men may deemthat you are worthilydeposed.

135
00:09:58.170 --> 00:10:00.270
Must I do so?

136
00:10:00.270 --> 00:10:03.970
And must I ravel out myweaved-up follies?

137
00:10:03.970 --> 00:10:07.770
Gentle Northumberland, if thyoffences were upon record,

138
00:10:07.770 --> 00:10:10.100
would it not shame thee inso fair a troop

139
00:10:10.100 --> 00:10:12.000
to read a lecture of them?

140
00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:13.170
If thou wouldst,

141
00:10:13.170 --> 00:10:15.370
there shouldst thou findone heinous article,

142
00:10:15.370 --> 00:10:17.130
containing the deposing ofa king

143
00:10:17.130 --> 00:10:19.730
and cracking the strongwarrant of an oath,

144
00:10:19.730 --> 00:10:24.570
marked with a blot, damnedin the book of heaven.

145
00:10:24.570 --> 00:10:29.670
Nay, all of you that standand look upon me

146
00:10:29.670 --> 00:10:32.830
whilst that my wretchednessdoth bait myself,

147
00:10:32.830 --> 00:10:35.370
though some of you withPilate wash your hands,

148
00:10:35.370 --> 00:10:37.530
showing an outward pity.

149
00:10:37.530 --> 00:10:45.670
Yet you Pilates have heredelivered me to my sour cross,

150
00:10:45.670 --> 00:10:49.170
and water cannot wash awayyour sin.

151
00:10:49.170 --> 00:10:50.170
My lord, dispatch.

152
00:10:50.170 --> 00:10:52.330
Read o'er these articles.

153
00:10:52.330 --> 00:10:55.930
Mine eyes are full oftears.

154
00:10:55.930 --> 00:11:00.270
I cannot see.

155
00:11:00.270 --> 00:11:03.900
And yet salt water blindsthem not so much

156
00:11:03.900 --> 00:11:06.800
but they can see a sort oftraitors here.

157
00:11:06.800 --> 00:11:09.700
Nay, if I turn mine eyesupon myself,

158
00:11:09.700 --> 00:11:11.430
I find myself a traitorwith the rest,

159
00:11:11.430 --> 00:11:14.130
for I have given here mysoul's consent

160
00:11:14.130 --> 00:11:16.770
to undeck the pompous bodyof a king,

161
00:11:16.770 --> 00:11:19.730
made glory base andsovereignty a slave,

162
00:11:19.730 --> 00:11:23.600
proud majesty a subject,state a peasant.

163
00:11:23.600 --> 00:11:24.600
My lord--

164
00:11:24.600 --> 00:11:32.800
No lord of thine, thouhaught, insulting man,

165
00:11:32.800 --> 00:11:34.970
nor no man's lord.

166
00:11:36.470 --> 00:11:40.630
I have no name, no title.

167
00:11:40.630 --> 00:11:42.300
No, not that name wasgiven me at the font,

168
00:11:42.300 --> 00:11:44.030
but 'tis usurped.

169
00:11:44.030 --> 00:11:45.170
Alack the heavy day

170
00:11:45.170 --> 00:11:47.370
that I have worn so manywinters out

171
00:11:47.370 --> 00:11:51.100
and know not now what nameto call myself.

172
00:11:52.300 --> 00:11:58.800
Oh, that I were a mockeryking of snow,

173
00:11:58.800 --> 00:12:04.030
standing before the sun ofBolingbroke,

174
00:12:04.030 --> 00:12:07.430
to melt myself away inwaterdrops.

175
00:12:14.170 --> 00:12:23.530
Good king, great king, andyet not greatly good,

176
00:12:23.530 --> 00:12:27.170
and if my word be sterlingyet in England,

177
00:12:27.170 --> 00:12:30.730
let it command a mirrorhither straight,

178
00:12:32.170 --> 00:12:36.570
that it may show me what aface I have

179
00:12:36.570 --> 00:12:39.530
since it is bankrupt ofHis Majesty.

180
00:12:41.470 --> 00:12:43.670
Go some of you and fetch alooking glass.

181
00:12:43.670 --> 00:12:45.630
Read o'er this paper whilethe glass doth come.

182
00:12:45.630 --> 00:12:48.370
Fiend, thou torment'st meere I come to hell.

183
00:12:48.370 --> 00:12:50.230
Urge it no more, my lordNorthumberland.

184
00:12:50.230 --> 00:12:51.630
The commons then will notbe satisfied.

185
00:12:51.630 --> 00:12:53.000
They shall be satisfied.

186
00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:55.830
I'll read enough when I dosee the very book indeed

187
00:12:55.830 --> 00:12:59.170
where all my sins arewrit, and that's myself.

188
00:13:01.530 --> 00:13:02.770
Give me the glass,

189
00:13:05.130 --> 00:13:07.230
and therein will I read.

190
00:13:17.030 --> 00:13:18.700
No deeper wrinkles yet?

191
00:13:20.900 --> 00:13:24.070
Hath sorrow struck so manyblows upon this face of mine,

192
00:13:25.070 --> 00:13:28.030
and made no deeper wounds?

193
00:13:30.100 --> 00:13:32.770
Oh, flattering glass,

194
00:13:32.770 --> 00:13:35.100
like to my followers inprosperity,

195
00:13:35.100 --> 00:13:36.930
thou dost beguile me.

196
00:13:39.670 --> 00:13:43.370
Was this face the face

197
00:13:43.370 --> 00:13:46.530
that every day under hishousehold roof

198
00:13:46.530 --> 00:13:49.030
did keep 10,000 men?

199
00:13:51.600 --> 00:13:59.200
Was this the face that,like the sun, did makebeholders wink?

200
00:14:01.570 --> 00:14:06.800
Is this the face whichfaced so many follies

201
00:14:06.800 --> 00:14:11.200
that was at last outfacedby Bolingbroke?

202
00:14:14.770 --> 00:14:17.270
A brittle glory shineth inthis face,

203
00:14:19.430 --> 00:14:24.000
as brittle as the glory isthe face.

204
00:14:27.670 --> 00:14:33.170
For there it lies, crackedin a hundred shivers.

205
00:14:35.170 --> 00:14:42.230
Mark, silent king, themoral of this sport.

206
00:14:44.830 --> 00:14:47.800
How soon my sorrow hathdestroyed my face.

207
00:14:50.330 --> 00:14:52.600
The shadow of your sorrowhath destroyed

208
00:14:52.600 --> 00:14:54.870
the shadow of your face.

209
00:14:54.870 --> 00:14:56.200
Say that again.

210
00:14:57.730 --> 00:15:00.270
The shadow of my sorrow.

211
00:15:00.770 --> 00:15:01.830
Ha!

212
00:15:06.130 --> 00:15:07.130
Let's see.

213
00:15:07.130 --> 00:15:09.600
'Tis very true.

214
00:15:09.600 --> 00:15:13.100
My grief lies all within.

215
00:15:13.100 --> 00:15:16.270
And these external mannersof lament

216
00:15:16.270 --> 00:15:20.730
are merely shadows to theunseen grief

217
00:15:20.730 --> 00:15:26.500
that swells with silencein the tortured soul.

218
00:15:27.700 --> 00:15:30.570
There lies the substance,

219
00:15:32.970 --> 00:15:37.300
and I thank thee, king,for thy great bounty

220
00:15:37.300 --> 00:15:40.730
that not only givest mecause to wail

221
00:15:40.730 --> 00:15:44.770
but teachest me the wayhow to lament the cause.

222
00:15:47.070 --> 00:15:52.730
I'll beg one boon, andthen be gone and troubleyou no more.

223
00:15:52.730 --> 00:15:53.730
Shall I obtain it?

224
00:15:53.730 --> 00:15:55.830
Name it, fair cousin.

225
00:15:55.830 --> 00:15:57.630
Fair cousin?

226
00:15:58.970 --> 00:16:01.400
I am greater than a king,

227
00:16:01.400 --> 00:16:04.270
for when I was a king,

228
00:16:04.270 --> 00:16:07.030
my flatterers were thenbut subjects.

229
00:16:07.030 --> 00:16:11.770
Being now a subject, I havea king here to myflatterer.

230
00:16:11.770 --> 00:16:15.970
Being so great, I have noneed to beg.

231
00:16:18.470 --> 00:16:19.500
Yet ask.

232
00:16:19.500 --> 00:16:21.100
And shall I have?

233
00:16:21.100 --> 00:16:22.470
You shall.

234
00:16:22.470 --> 00:16:24.430
Then give me leave to go.

235
00:16:25.830 --> 00:16:26.830
Whither?

236
00:16:26.830 --> 00:16:34.970
Whither you will, so Iwere from your sights.

237
00:16:34.970 --> 00:16:38.300
Go, some of you convey himto the tower.

238
00:16:38.300 --> 00:16:43.430
Oh, good.

239
00:16:43.430 --> 00:16:46.700
Convey?

240
00:16:46.700 --> 00:16:50.670
Conveyers are you all

241
00:16:50.670 --> 00:16:57.200
that rise thus nimbly by atrue king's fall.

242
00:17:02.930 --> 00:17:08.730
On Wednesday next, wesolemnly set down ourcoronation.

243
00:17:08.730 --> 00:17:10.470
Lords, prepare yourselves.

244
00:17:11.400 --> 00:17:14.730
God save the king!

245
00:17:14.730 --> 00:17:17.230
God save the king!

246
00:17:20.670 --> 00:17:23.530
A woeful pageant have wehere beheld.

247
00:17:23.530 --> 00:17:26.070
The woe's to come.

248
00:17:26.070 --> 00:17:28.630
The children yet unborn

249
00:17:28.630 --> 00:17:31.570
shall feel this day assharp to them as thorn.

250
00:17:38.430 --> 00:17:42.030
You holy clergymen, isthere no plot

251
00:17:42.030 --> 00:17:45.330
to rid the realm of thispernicious blot?

252
00:17:53.300 --> 00:17:55.070
This way the king willcome.

253
00:17:57.800 --> 00:18:01.370
This is the way to JuliusCaesar's ill-erected tower,

254
00:18:01.370 --> 00:18:04.070
to whose flint bosom mycondemned lord

255
00:18:04.070 --> 00:18:07.030
is doomed a prisoner byproud Bolingbroke.

256
00:18:09.170 --> 00:18:13.000
Here let us rest, if thisrebellious earth

257
00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:15.830
have any resting for hertrue king's queen.

258
00:18:18.930 --> 00:18:24.270
But soft, but see, orrather do not see,

259
00:18:24.270 --> 00:18:27.830
my fair rose wither.

260
00:18:27.830 --> 00:18:30.670
Yet look up, behold,

261
00:18:30.670 --> 00:18:33.270
that you in pity maydissolve to dew

262
00:18:33.270 --> 00:18:36.930
and wash him fresh againwith true love tears.

