00:18:38.270 --> 00:18:41.070
Ah, thou, the model whereold Troy did stand,

264
00:18:42.500 --> 00:18:46.900
thou map of honor, thouKing Richard's tomb,

265
00:18:46.900 --> 00:18:50.000
and not King Richard.

266
00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.170
Thou most beauteous inn,

267
00:18:52.170 --> 00:18:54.300
why should hard-favoredgrief be lodged in thee,

268
00:18:54.300 --> 00:18:56.700
when triumph is become analehouse guest?

269
00:18:56.700 --> 00:18:59.270
Join not with grief, fairwoman.

270
00:18:59.270 --> 00:19:02.800
Do not so, to make my endtoo sudden.

271
00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:04.970
Learn, good soul,

272
00:19:04.970 --> 00:19:09.070
to think our former statea happy dream,

273
00:19:09.070 --> 00:19:11.330
from which awaked,

274
00:19:11.330 --> 00:19:15.430
the truth of what we areshows us but this.

275
00:19:15.430 --> 00:19:19.100
I am sworn brother, sweet,to grim necessity,

276
00:19:19.100 --> 00:19:21.900
and he and I will keep aleague till death.

277
00:19:23.170 --> 00:19:27.500
Hie thee to France andcloister thee in somereligious house.

278
00:19:27.500 --> 00:19:31.470
Our holy lives must win anew world's crown,

279
00:19:31.470 --> 00:19:37.800
which our profane hourshere have stricken down.

280
00:19:37.800 --> 00:19:41.400
What, is my Richard bothin shape and mind

281
00:19:41.400 --> 00:19:44.230
transformed and weakened?

282
00:19:44.230 --> 00:19:47.630
Hath Bolingbroke deposedthine intellect?

283
00:19:47.630 --> 00:19:50.100
Hath he been in thy heart?

284
00:19:50.100 --> 00:19:53.000
The lion dying thrustethforth his paw

285
00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:55.030
and wounds the earth, ifnothing else,

286
00:19:55.030 --> 00:19:57.700
with rage to beo'erpower'd.

287
00:19:57.700 --> 00:20:00.200
And wilt thou, pupil-like,

288
00:20:00.200 --> 00:20:03.770
take the correctionmildly, kiss the rod,

289
00:20:03.770 --> 00:20:06.670
and fawn on rage with basehumility,

290
00:20:06.670 --> 00:20:10.400
which art a lion and theking of beasts?

291
00:20:10.400 --> 00:20:14.130
King of beasts indeed.

292
00:20:14.130 --> 00:20:18.700
If aught but beasts, Ihad still been a happyking of men.

293
00:20:20.170 --> 00:20:25.470
Good sometimes queen, preparethee hence for France.

294
00:20:25.470 --> 00:20:30.070
Think I am dead and thateven here thou takest,

295
00:20:30.070 --> 00:20:32.870
as from my deathbed, thylast living leave.

296
00:20:34.770 --> 00:20:37.200
In winter's tediousnights,

297
00:20:37.200 --> 00:20:39.630
sit by the fire with goodold folks

298
00:20:39.630 --> 00:20:43.770
and let them tell theetales of woeful ages longago betid.

299
00:20:45.170 --> 00:20:48.800
And ere thou bid good night,to quit their griefs,

300
00:20:48.800 --> 00:20:52.570
tell thou the lamentabletale of me

301
00:20:52.570 --> 00:20:56.270
and send the hearersweeping to their beds.

302
00:20:56.270 --> 00:20:58.830
For why, the senselessbrands will sympathize

303
00:20:58.830 --> 00:21:01.500
the heavy accent of thymoving tongue

304
00:21:01.500 --> 00:21:05.830
and in compassion weep thefire out.

305
00:21:05.830 --> 00:21:10.370
And some will mourn inashes, some coal black,

306
00:21:10.370 --> 00:21:14.500
for the deposing of arightful king.

307
00:21:14.500 --> 00:21:18.700
My lord, the mind ofBolingbroke is changed.

308
00:21:18.700 --> 00:21:21.130
You must to Pomfret, notunto the tower.

309
00:21:21.130 --> 00:21:22.600
And, madam, there is orderta'en for you.

310
00:21:22.600 --> 00:21:25.800
With all swift speed youmust away to France.

311
00:21:25.800 --> 00:21:29.170
Northumberland, thouladder wherewithal

312
00:21:29.170 --> 00:21:31.570
the mounting Bolingbrokeascends my throne,

313
00:21:31.570 --> 00:21:34.200
the time shall not be manyhours of age

314
00:21:34.200 --> 00:21:37.170
more than it is ere foulsin gathering head

315
00:21:37.170 --> 00:21:39.530
shall break intocorruption.

316
00:21:39.530 --> 00:21:40.730
Thou shalt think,

317
00:21:40.730 --> 00:21:43.870
though he divide the realmand give thee half,

318
00:21:43.870 --> 00:21:47.600
it is too little, helpinghim to all.

319
00:21:47.600 --> 00:21:49.500
And he shall think thatthou

320
00:21:49.500 --> 00:21:51.870
which know'st the way toplant unrightful kings

321
00:21:51.870 --> 00:21:55.170
wilt know again, beingne'er so little urged,

322
00:21:55.170 --> 00:21:57.930
another way to pluck himheadlong

323
00:21:57.930 --> 00:22:00.370
from the usurped throne.

324
00:22:00.370 --> 00:22:04.070
The love of wicked menconverts to fear,

325
00:22:04.070 --> 00:22:05.830
that fear to hate,

326
00:22:05.830 --> 00:22:07.530
and hate turns one or both

327
00:22:07.530 --> 00:22:11.070
to worthy danger anddeserved death.

328
00:22:11.070 --> 00:22:16.800
My guilt be on my head,and there an end.

329
00:22:16.800 --> 00:22:19.370
Take leave and part, foryou must part forthwith.

330
00:22:19.370 --> 00:22:20.600
Doubly divorced.

331
00:22:20.600 --> 00:22:23.970
Bad men, you violate atwofold marriage,

332
00:22:23.970 --> 00:22:25.730
'twixt my crown and me,

333
00:22:25.730 --> 00:22:29.200
and then betwixt me and mymarried wife.

334
00:22:29.200 --> 00:22:32.370
Let me unkiss the oath'twixt thee and me.

335
00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:41.830
And yet not so, for with akiss 'twas made.

336
00:22:41.830 --> 00:22:44.400
Part us, Northumberland--

337
00:22:44.400 --> 00:22:45.730
I toward the north,

338
00:22:45.730 --> 00:22:49.270
where shivering cold andsickness pines the clime.

339
00:22:49.270 --> 00:22:50.570
My wife to France,

340
00:22:50.570 --> 00:22:54.100
from whence, set forth inpomp,

341
00:22:54.100 --> 00:22:58.100
she came adorned hitherlike sweet May,

342
00:22:58.100 --> 00:23:01.430
sent back like Hallowmasor short'st of day.

343
00:23:01.430 --> 00:23:02.430
And must we be divided?

344
00:23:02.430 --> 00:23:03.530
Must we part?

345
00:23:03.530 --> 00:23:11.530
Aye, hand from hand, mylove, and heart from heart.

346
00:23:11.530 --> 00:23:14.200
Banish us both and sendthe king with me.

347
00:23:14.200 --> 00:23:16.670
That were some love butlittle policy.

348
00:23:16.670 --> 00:23:18.930
Then whither he goes,thither let me go.

349
00:23:18.930 --> 00:23:22.770
So two, together weeping,make one woe.

350
00:23:22.770 --> 00:23:26.330
Weep thou for me inFrance, I for thee here.

351
00:23:26.330 --> 00:23:30.130
Better far off than near,be ne'er the near.

352
00:23:30.130 --> 00:23:33.070
Go, count thy way withsighs.

353
00:23:33.070 --> 00:23:35.200
I mine with groans.

354
00:23:35.200 --> 00:23:40.970
So longest way shall havethe longest moans.

355
00:23:40.970 --> 00:23:45.370
Twice for one step I'llgroan, the way being short,

356
00:23:45.370 --> 00:23:48.370
and piece the way out witha heavy heart.

357
00:23:48.370 --> 00:23:51.400
Come, come, in wooingsorrow let's be brief,

358
00:23:51.400 --> 00:23:53.930
since, wedding it, thereis such length in grief.

359
00:23:53.930 --> 00:23:58.070
One kiss shall stop ourmouths, and dumbly part.

360
00:24:02.770 --> 00:24:05.500
Thus give I mine, and thustake I thy heart.

361
00:24:05.500 --> 00:24:07.370
Give me mine own again.

362
00:24:07.370 --> 00:24:11.730
'Twere no good part totake on me to keep andkill thy heart.

363
00:24:20.030 --> 00:24:22.200
Now I have mine own again.

364
00:24:22.200 --> 00:24:27.000
Be gone that I may striveto kill it with a groan.

365
00:24:31.770 --> 00:24:36.000
We make woe wanton withthis fond delay.

366
00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:38.730
Once more, adieu.

367
00:24:38.730 --> 00:24:40.670
The rest let sorrow say.

